<h1>Hyacinthus orientalis – Common Hyacinth</h1>

<p>
<a href="/o/page?o=word&w=Hyacinth">Hyacinth</a> orientalis, commonly known as the Common Hyacinth, is a fragrant spring-flowering bulb widely cultivated in gardens for its dense spikes of colorful blooms.
</p>

<h2>Description</h2>
<p>
This species produces compact flower spikes made up of many star-shaped blossoms in shades of blue, purple, pink, white, and red, with a strong sweet fragrance.
</p>

<h2>Etymology</h2>
<p>
“Hyacinthus” comes from Greek mythology, named after Hyacinthus, a youth associated with beauty and tragic transformation.
</p>

<h2>Taxonomy</h2>
<p>
Family: Asparagaceae<br>
Genus: Hyacinthus<br>
Species: H. orientalis
</p>

<h2>Distribution and Habitat</h2>
<p>
Native to the eastern Mediterranean region and parts of the Middle East, it grows naturally in rocky, well-drained soils.
</p>

<h2>Ecology</h2>
<p>
Attracts early-season pollinators such as bees and is widely cultivated as an ornamental plant worldwide.
</p>

<h2>Cultivation</h2>
<ul>
<li>Full sun to partial shade</li>
<li>Well-drained soil</li>
<li>Planted from bulbs in autumn</li>
<li>Requires a cold period to flower well</li>
</ul>

<h3>Cultivars</h3>
<ul>
<li>‘Delft Blue’ – classic blue flowers</li>
<li>‘Carnegie’ – pure white blooms</li>
<li>‘Jan Bos’ – deep pink variety</li>
</ul>

<h2>Symbolism</h2>
<p>
Represents rebirth, constancy, and sincerity, often associated with spring renewal.
</p>

